      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Shrinkage, a lost piece of the puzzle, is a real drag on the inventory turnover ratio. You need to account for it before you can get a clean picture of how fast you're moving your goods.  Think of shrinkage as a hidden, uncounted inventory that's basically just gone, which means your reported inventory is inflated.\n\nHere's the basic idea: you need to adjust your Cost of Goods Sold (COGS) or your average inventory figure to reflect the true amount of goods you *actually* sold versus what you *thought* you had.\n\nThe standard Inventory Turnover Ratio is:\n\n$$\\text{Inventory Turnover} = \\frac{\\text{Cost of Goods Sold (COGS)}}{\\text{Average Inventory}}$$\n\nTo factor in shrinkage, you need to adjust the **Average Inventory**. If you have shrinkage, your reported inventory is too high, so you need to subtract the estimated shrinkage from your average inventory figure to get a more accurate denominator.\n\n$$\\text{Adjusted Average Inventory} = \\text{Average Inventory} - \\text{Shrinkage Value}$$\n\nThen, you plug that adjusted number back into the formula:\n\n$$\\text{Adjusted Inventory Turnover} = \\frac{\\text",
